  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "I. Pollux, Rhetor from Naucratis, author of an Onomastikon, 2nd cent. AD: hetor from Naucratis (Egypt), 2nd half of the 2nd cent. AD (each of the 10 bks. of his Onomastikón is preceded by a dedication to the emperor Commodus), pupil of Hadrianus ... (a pupil of Herodes Atticus). He assumed the chair of rhetoric in Athens (not before 178) following a competition with his rival, the Atticist Phrynichus. He was also famed for the beauty of his speech (cf. Philostr. VS 2,12)
    he died at the age of 58...." Tosi, Renzo (Bologna). "Iulius." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and
    Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2010. Brill Online. Tufts University Library. 07 October 2010</mads:note>
